
[1]lamp

   LAMP, n. [L. lampas; Gr. to shine; Heb.]

   1. A vessel for containing oil to be burned by means of a wick; or a
   light, a burning wick inserted in a vessel of oil. Hence,

   2. Figuratively, a light of any kind. The moon is called the lamp of
   heaven.

   Thy gentle eyes send forth a quickening spirit, to feed the dying lamp
   of life within me.

   Lamp of safety, or safety lamp, a lamp for lighting coal mines, without
   exposing workmen to the explosion of inflammable air.
